Note that in Fig. 2, Loss2, reflecting the IR condition,
remains 00 throughout the whole training process. The training LOSS is
dominated by Loss3, which is high at the begining and approaches 00 later.
This means that WBB is satisfied by the trained network except for some rare
cases. For example, in Table 2, except for the
rare case where the cost types of all data owners exceed a threshold (with
a prior probability less than 10−2superscript10210^{-2}), Loss3 is 00. On the other hand,
Loss1, the unfairness level, remains positive. This is because by definition
the unfairness function being 00 implies a linear payment structure, which
cannot satisfy IR and WBB.

Such a two-part payment structure is also revealed in Table
1 and Table 2.
We can see that if data owner i𝑖i’s cost type is high, ηisubscript𝜂𝑖\eta_{i} becomes
00. Data owners with equal cost types are included on a
first-come-first-accepted basis. The binary nature of ηisubscript𝜂𝑖\eta_{i} leads to the
two-part structure of τisubscript𝜏𝑖\tau_{i} and pisubscript𝑝𝑖p_{i}. On the other hand, the payment
adjustment term, hi+gisubscriptℎ𝑖subscript𝑔𝑖h_{i}+g_{i}, is relatively smooth. It increases with qisubscript𝑞𝑖q_{i} but
is not very sensitive to γisubscript𝛾𝑖\gamma_{i}. This is because 𝜸𝜸\bm{\gamma} is not
included in the unfairness function in the specification of our experiment.
